You say you&#39;re using `java.net` so I&#39;m assuming that you&#39;re using something like a `java.net.ServerSocket`. If you call [setSoTimeout][1] on your instance of `ServerSocket`, you will be able to set a timeout for your socket. Then, when you block during calls to [accept][2], your `ServerSocket` will keep track of the timeout. As you can see in the documentation, accept throws a `SocketTimeoutException` if a timeout has been defined and the wait time has exceeded the timeout. So, you&#39;ll end up with something like this (forgive me for being a bit rusty on `Socket`s):
``` Java
try(ServerSocket ssock = new ServerSocket(...))
{
    ssock.setSoTimeout(10_000); // 10 second timeout
    while(true)
    {
        Socket csock = ssock.accept();
        methodToStartThreadThatHandlesClientSocket(csock);
    }
}
catch(SocketTimeoutException ste)
{
    //handle socket timeout
}
catch(Exception other)
{
    //handle other exceptions
}
```


  [1]: https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/13/docs/api/java.base/java/net/ServerSocket.html#setSoTimeout(int)
  [2]: https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/13/docs/api/java.base/java/net/ServerSocket.html#accept()

